body:
## Problem: 

_From V3SchedTiming.cpp:_
```cpp
                    // If it's fork..join, we can refer to variables from the parent process
                } else {
                    // TODO: It is possible to relax this by allowing the use of such variables up
                    // until the first await. Also, variables defined within a forked process
                    // (inside a begin) are extracted out by V3Begin, so they also trigger this
                    // error. Preventing this (or detecting such cases and moving the vars back)
                    // would also allow for using them freely.
```

Unfortunately it looks like it isn't so simple as the proposed solution makes it to be, because when variables don't get extracted with V3Begin, they remain within function's body instead of being moved under a `SCOPE` node, which results in their addresses changing once a `TASK` is converted to a `CFUNC`, invalidating all references. However, we cannot move them out of the fork, because then their lifetimes could be outlived by the spawned processes.

This highlights a **bigger issue**, that Verilator is currently unable to pass local variables to processes that might outlive them.
## Solution

My solution is to identify all processes under `fork..join_none` and `fork..join_any` statements that "capture" any non-static variables and transform them into separate tasks. The sub-ASTs of those processes would be replaced with calls to those tasks to which any captures will be passed by value as arguments to these calls. Any references to the captured variables would be replaced with references to task's arguments. These newly generated tasks will later be given their own scopes, independent from the scopes of their parents.

### Variable capturing details:

* All variables are **captured by value**, unless their lifetime is static (eg. their exist within a module).
* Variables are captured **implicitly**. I found IEEE 1800-2017 to be very unclear about it. Page 212 suggests that this should be illegal, yet various example, like the one on page 204 seem to do exactly that. So I decided that anything that would actually require a reference instead of copy should throw an error. See the point below.
* Implicit captures are allowed **only for read access**.

## Caveats
* No support for _block_item_declaration_ sections of `fork..join*` blocks
* ~~Delaying a block/statement under a fork will delay the initialization of variables within generated procedure, making it possible (and likely) for parent process to go out of the current scope before the initialization happens. Since arguments to the spawned process' procedure are passed by reference, once the initialization happens the references might no longer point to the correct data. This is because the values for local copies of arguments get assigned within `// Body` section of generated `CFUNC` instead of `// Init` and the entirety of `// Body` gets prefaced with a `co_await` statement that halts the coroutine and passes it to scheduler if the execution of the statement was to be delayed. I'm not sure why is it this way.~~ **EDIT:** Seems that for some reason this is no longer an issue, or at least I haven't seen a spot where that would happen in the current version of this PR ([744d9b8](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/pull/4253/commits/744d9b8b261e8716f5df126b970337b1fdf9de5c)).
